Note:
============================================================================
P2-B DISPATCHER API SURFACE — OpenBSD-specific BSD-syscall-number procs
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
These four BSD-syscall-number procs complete the 66-proc bare-name dispatcher
API surface on openbsd_x64. Each entry resolves a name that the cross-platform
dispatcher (`compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa`) expects to
exist on every platform but whose OpenBSD-specific value or sentinel must be
encoded here rather than in the dispatcher ladder.

Specific routing rationale per proc:
  SYS_BRK -> 17: OpenBSD retains the historical 4.4BSD heap-break syscall but
    names it `obreak` in `sys/sys/syscall.h` (entry 17). The kernel ABI is
    identical to Linux `brk(2)`: a single `void *nsize` argument, return is
    the resulting break address (or -ENOMEM on failure). We alias SYS_BRK to
    the existing SYS_OBREAK constant (also 17 in this file) so cross-platform
    callers can use the Linux-canonical name without conditional compilation.
    Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 17 (`SYS_obreak`); `sys/kern/
    kern_resource.c` `sys_obreak()`.

  SYS_EXIT_GROUP -> 1: OpenBSD has no `exit_group` syscall. The kernel's
    process model collapses the entire task on `exit(2)` (entry 1) because
    OpenBSD threads share an `struct process` and `sys_exit()` invokes
    `exit1(EXIT_THREAD_NOCHECK)` on every thread in the same process via
    `proc_thrunlink()`. We therefore alias SYS_EXIT_GROUP to SYS_EXIT=1 so
    cross-platform callers obtain identical "terminate all threads"
    semantics without conditional dispatch. Source: OpenBSD `sys/kern/
    kern_exit.c` `sys_exit()` / `exit1()`; OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h`
    entry 1 (`SYS_exit`).

  SYS_CREAT -> -1: Historical BSD assigned syscall 8 to `creat(2)`. On modern
    OpenBSD that slot was reused for `__tfork` (the thread-fork primitive
    used by libpthread). The dispatcher API contract nonetheless requires
    that every platform export SYS_CREAT for cross-platform symbol-table
    parity, but returning the literal 8 here is catastrophically dangerous:
    any caller that issues `syscall_N(SYS_CREAT(), ...)` would dispatch
    `__tfork` (entry 8) with creat-shaped arguments, interpreting the path
    pointer as a `struct __tfork *` and dereferencing `tf_tcb` — guaranteed
    memory corruption or kernel-side fault. We therefore return -1 as a
    runtime error sentinel so that any accidental direct dispatch on
    openbsd_x64 fails fast through the `is_error()` helper rather than
    silently invoking `__tfork`. The dedicated SYS_TFORK entry (already
    defined at slot 8) remains the correct route for callers that actually
    intend thread-fork dispatch; SYS_CREAT must NEVER be dispatched
    directly on openbsd_x64. Production callers obtain creat(2) semantics
    via `syscall_open(path, O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC, mode)` — the
    documented and only correct route. Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h`
    entry 8 (`SYS___tfork`); historical 4.4BSD `creat` syscall in slot 8;
    OpenBSD-current `sys/kern/kern_fork.c` `sys___tfork()`.

  SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY -> -1: OpenBSD provides no kernel-level CPU affinity
    interface. The kernel scheduler `sys/kern/kern_sched.c` makes
    process-to-CPU placement decisions itself based on per-CPU run queues;
    user space cannot bind a thread to a specific CPU. The closest available
    facility is CPU-count query via `sysctl(2)` (entry 202) on `KERN_NCPUONLINE`
    name `hw.ncpuonline` (`sys/sys/sysctl.h` `HW_NCPUONLINE`). We return -1
    as a runtime sentinel; callers detecting -1 must bridge through `sysctl`
    with `mib = [CTL_HW, HW_NCPUONLINE]` to obtain the online CPU count, then
    treat affinity as a hint rather than a guarantee. Source: OpenBSD
    `sys/kern/kern_sysctl.c` `kern_sysctl_dispatch()` HW branch; absence of
    any `sched_*` syscall in OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each proc is a nullary `Process` returning the constant Integer that the
bare-name dispatcher's `SYS_X from OpenBSDX64` lookup will resolve to on
openbsd_x64 targets. The dispatcher (assembly/syscall.runa) selects the
platform via `platform_index_for_key("openbsd_x64") = 12` and then calls
`proc SYS_X from OpenBSDX64` directly; the returned integer is then forwarded
to `syscall_N` wrappers which load it into RAX and execute the `syscall`
instruction (OpenBSD uses no syscall-class mask; raw entries are issued
directly, unlike Darwin's 0x2000000 OR-mask).

Procs returning a valid positive entry (SYS_BRK=17, SYS_EXIT_GROUP=1) are
intended for direct `syscall_N` dispatch. SYS_CREAT returns -1 as a
runtime error sentinel on openbsd_x64 because slot 8 collides with the
modern `__tfork` syscall (the dedicated SYS_TFORK proc covers that slot
for callers that genuinely want thread-fork dispatch). SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY
likewise returns -1 as a runtime sentinel because no native CPU-affinity
syscall exists on OpenBSD. Both sentinels are recognized by the
dispatcher's `is_error` helper, so callers can gate either syscall behind
`If is_error(SYS_CREAT()) is equal to 0:` / `If is_error(SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY())
is equal to 0:` to detect the unavailable-syscall condition and take the
documented bridge path (`syscall_open` with `O_CREAT|O_WRONLY|O_TRUNC` for
creat semantics; `sysctl(2)` on `KERN_HW`/`HW_NCPUONLINE` for the
affinity-CPU-count substitute). Direct `syscall_N(SYS_CREAT(), ...)`
dispatch on openbsd_x64 will now fail fast at the syscall instruction
(RAX=-1 is an invalid syscall number, yielding -ENOSYS) instead of
silently invoking `__tfork` with creat-shaped arguments and corrupting
kernel state.

No additional state is mutated; these are pure constant-returning getters
with deterministic behavior across every OpenBSD release because the
underlying syscall numbers (`sys/sys/syscall.h`) are part of the stable
OpenBSD kernel ABI and have not changed since OpenBSD 6.0 for the entries
referenced here.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
All four procs are constant-return; the HIR -> MIR constant-fold pass is
expected to inline them at every call site, leaving zero call overhead in
the emitted machine code. Do not introduce conditionals, side effects, or
runtime computation in these bodies — the runtime cost of fetching a
syscall number must remain a single `mov rax, imm32` instruction at the
caller. The -1 sentinel branch for SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY should be
evaluated at the caller's hot-path entry (e.g. once at thread startup
for affinity initialization), not on every scheduling decision, so the
inliner can fold both the SYS_X return and the `is_error` check into a
single comparison-and-branch on caller hot paths.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a syscall number carries no privilege escalation: the OpenBSD
kernel validates every syscall argument independently before honoring the
trap. Callers must, however, observe three correctness constraints:

  1. SYS_CREAT COLLISION — CRITICAL HAZARD. Historical 4.4BSD assigned
     syscall 8 to `creat(2)`; modern OpenBSD repurposed slot 8 for
     `__tfork` (the thread-fork primitive consumed by libpthread). Returning
     the historical value 8 from SYS_CREAT would cause any caller that
     issues `syscall_3(SYS_CREAT(), path, mode, 0)` to invoke `__tfork`
     instead — the kernel would interpret `path` as a `struct __tfork *`,
     dereference `tf_tcb` from the supposed struct, and either corrupt
     kernel state, attempt to register a userland pointer as a TCB, or
     create a thread with the caller's stack pointing into the path
     string. This is a catastrophic misdispatch — a SAFETY hazard on every
     OpenBSD-current kernel, indistinguishable from a deliberate
     privilege-escalation primitive given the right path-string layout.
     This module therefore returns SYS_CREAT = -1 (runtime error sentinel)
     so that any direct dispatch attempt fails fast with -ENOSYS at the
     syscall instruction rather than silently invoking `__tfork`. The
     dedicated SYS_TFORK proc (returning 8) is the correct entry point for
     callers that legitimately need thread-fork dispatch; the two procs are
     deliberately separated to prevent the collision from manifesting as a
     runtime safety bug. Production code MUST route create-with-truncate
     through `syscall_open` with `O_CREAT|O_WRONLY|O_TRUNC` — this is the
     only correct creat(2)-equivalent path on openbsd_x64 (and is the
     portable path that should be used on every platform regardless).

  2. SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY returning -1 means the kernel does not support
     CPU pinning. Callers must NOT treat -1 as a non-error CPU mask;
     iterating from 0 to result-as-bits falsely reports no online CPUs.
     Use `is_error()` to gate the sentinel and bridge through `sysctl(2)`
     on `hw.ncpuonline`.

  3. The -1 sentinel returned by SYS_CREAT and SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY is
     deliberately a value that no valid OpenBSD syscall number can
     occupy (syscall numbers are non-negative; the kernel rejects negative
     RAX values with -ENOSYS during `syscallenter()` validation). Callers
     MUST use `is_error()` to detect the sentinel BEFORE forwarding the
     return value to a `syscall_N` dispatcher — passing -1 to
     `syscall_N` is harmless on OpenBSD (kernel returns -ENOSYS) but is
     wasted work; well-formed callers branch on the sentinel and take
     the documented bridge path without issuing the trap.

SYS_EXIT_GROUP=1 inherits all security properties of `exit(2)`: the calling
process surrenders all resources, file descriptors are closed, mmap mappings
are torn down via `vmcmd_munmap`, and the parent receives SIGCHLD. No
caller-supplied pointer is dereferenced.

SYS_BRK=17 inherits all security properties of `obreak(2)`: the kernel
validates the supplied break address against the process's `vm_daddr +
vm_dsize` limits (`sys/kern/kern_resource.c` `sys_obreak()`) and refuses
requests that extend the heap past `data` resource limits or that
collide with mmap'd regions. A malicious caller cannot exploit this
proc beyond what `obreak(2)` already permits.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "openbsd_x64_SYS_BRK" returns Integer:
    Return 17  Note: Aliases SYS_OBREAK (entry 17); OpenBSD names heap-break syscall obreak
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Aliases SYS_EXIT (entry 1); OpenBSD task collapses on last thread exit
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_SYS_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Runtime error sentinel — slot 8 collides with __tfork on modern OpenBSD; use SYS_TFORK for thread-fork, use syscall_open with O_CREAT|O_WRONLY|O_TRUNC for creat semantics
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: No native syscall — bridge via sysctl(KERN_HW, HW_NCPUONLINE) for CPU count
End Process

