Note:
============================================================================
P2-B DISPATCHER API SURFACE — Cross-platform constant aliases
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
These six constants complete the cross-platform constant set that the
dispatcher API surface expects to find on every platform. Each one is a
verbatim numeric alias for an OpenBSD-native value that already exists in
this file under a different (BSD-historical) name, OR a POSIX-stable value
that is identical across every Unix-like system.

  MAP_ANONYMOUS -> 4096: Linux/POSIX-canonical spelling for MAP_ANON
    (already defined as 4096 = 0x1000 above). OpenBSD's `sys/sys/mman.h`
    defines only `MAP_ANON`; we expose MAP_ANONYMOUS for code portability
    so cross-platform `mmap` calls do not need conditional compilation.
    Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/mman.h` `MAP_ANON 0x1000`.

  MODE_0644 -> 420 (0644 octal = rw-r--r--): POSIX file mode constant.
    Identical across OpenBSD, Linux, Darwin, FreeBSD, NetBSD: 420 decimal
    encodes `S_IRUSR|S_IWUSR|S_IRGRP|S_IROTH` (0o644).

  MODE_0755 -> 493 (0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x): POSIX file mode constant.
    Identical across every Unix; 493 decimal encodes `S_IRWXU|S_IRGRP|
    S_IXGRP|S_IROTH|S_IXOTH` (0o755).

  SEEK_SET -> 0: POSIX-stable `lseek(2)` `whence` argument; identical
    across every Unix (OpenBSD `sys/sys/unistd.h` `SEEK_SET 0`).

  SEEK_CUR -> 1: POSIX-stable `lseek(2)` `whence` argument; identical
    across every Unix (OpenBSD `sys/sys/unistd.h` `SEEK_CUR 1`).

  SEEK_END -> 2: POSIX-stable `lseek(2)` `whence` argument; identical
    across every Unix (OpenBSD `sys/sys/unistd.h` `SEEK_END 2`).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each proc is a nullary `Process` returning the constant Integer that the
bare-name dispatcher's `CONST_X from OpenBSDX64` lookup resolves to. The
dispatcher (assembly/syscall.runa) routes every cross-platform constant
through this layer so callers can use the Linux/POSIX-canonical spelling
(MAP_ANONYMOUS, MODE_0644, MODE_0755, SEEK_SET, SEEK_CUR, SEEK_END) on
every supported platform without conditional compilation. MAP_ANONYMOUS
and MAP_ANON intentionally share the same return value (4096) because
they refer to the same OpenBSD `mmap` flag bit (0x1000); both spellings
are accepted to preserve source-level portability across Linux/Darwin/BSD.

These constants must not be confused with the OpenBSD-specific MAP_STACK
(16384 = 0x4000), which is a separate flag that requests stack-grow-down
semantics and is required by OpenBSD's W^X enforcement for any
`mmap(...,PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,...)` region that will hold a thread stack
under `pthread_attr_setstack`.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
All six procs are constant-return; the HIR -> MIR constant-fold pass
inlines them at every call site, leaving zero call overhead in the
emitted machine code. Each call becomes a single `mov rax, imm32`
instruction at the caller. Do not introduce conditionals, side effects,
or runtime computation in these bodies.

MODE_0644 and MODE_0755 are intended for use as the `mode` argument of
`syscall_open` (when `O_CREAT` is set in `flags`); both values are
deliberately encoded in decimal rather than octal because the Runa
front-end currently lexes integer literals in decimal only — the
Runtime semantic remains 0644 / 0755 octal as documented in the
trailing `Note:` on each Return.

SEEK_SET / SEEK_CUR / SEEK_END are intended for use as the `whence`
argument of `syscall_lseek`; their numeric values (0, 1, 2) are part of
the POSIX-stable ABI and are identical across every Unix-like kernel,
so no platform-specific dispatch is needed beyond the constant-fold.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a constant integer carries no privilege; these procs are pure
getters with no side effects. The constants are returned as Integer
(64-bit signed) because Runa's primitive integer type is Integer; the
kernel-side `mmap`/`open`/`lseek` syscall signatures accept these as
the appropriate sub-width (32-bit for `flags`/`whence`, mode_t for
`mode`), and the syscall ABI's argument-zero-extension handles the
width conversion implicitly.

MAP_ANONYMOUS (0x1000) on OpenBSD requires that `fd` be -1 and `offset`
be 0 when passed to `mmap(2)`; the kernel will return -EINVAL if these
constraints are violated. Callers building anonymous mappings must pair
this flag with MAP_PRIVATE (or MAP_SHARED for sharable scratch) to obtain
defined semantics — OpenBSD's `vm_mmap.c` `sys_mmap()` enforces the
"exactly one of MAP_PRIVATE/MAP_SHARED" precondition.

MODE_0644 / MODE_0755 are passed to `open(2)`/`mkdir(2)` only when
`O_CREAT` is set in the open flags; the kernel applies the process
`umask` to compute the final mode. Callers must NOT pre-apply umask
themselves — that is the kernel's responsibility.

SEEK_SET / SEEK_CUR / SEEK_END carry no security state; they direct
file-offset arithmetic only.
@End Security_Scope

