Note:
============================================================================
P2-B DISPATCHER API SURFACE — Dispatcher-named wrapper procs (Wave 1)
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
These ten high-level wrappers complete the 66-proc dispatcher API surface
for openbsd_x64. Each wraps a single OpenBSD syscall under the canonical
`syscall_<name>` spelling that the cross-platform dispatcher
(`compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa`) expects on every
platform; pre-existing wrappers in this file use BSD-historical names
(`read`, `write`, `open`, `close`, `exit`, `mmap`, `munmap`, `lseek`),
which the dispatcher does not consume — only the prefixed
`syscall_<name>` form is dispatched.

Specific wrapping rationale per proc:

  syscall_read -> SYS_READ (3) via syscall_3: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `read(fd, buf, nbyte)`. Three Integer arguments, returns bytes read or
    -errno. Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 3 (`SYS_read`);
    `sys/kern/sys_generic.c` `sys_read()`.

  syscall_write -> SYS_WRITE (4) via syscall_3: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `write(fd, buf, nbyte)`. Same argument shape as read. Source: OpenBSD
    `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 4 (`SYS_write`); `sys/kern/sys_generic.c`
    `sys_write()`.

  syscall_open -> SYS_OPEN (5) via syscall_3: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `open(path, flags, mode)`. The third argument `mode` is interpreted by
    the kernel only when `O_CREAT` is set in `flags`; passing 0 when
    O_CREAT is unset is permitted but the kernel ignores it. This is also
    the canonical path for emulating `creat(2)` semantics on openbsd_x64
    (caller passes `O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC` in flags). Source: OpenBSD
    `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 5 (`SYS_open`); `sys/kern/vfs_syscalls.c`
    `sys_open()`.

  syscall_close -> SYS_CLOSE (6) via syscall_1: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `close(fd)`. Returns 0 on success, -errno on failure. Source: OpenBSD
    `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 6 (`SYS_close`); `sys/kern/kern_descrip.c`
    `sys_close()`.

  syscall_exit -> SYS_EXIT (1) via syscall_1: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `exit(status)`. Does not return; the kernel destroys the task and all
    its threads (see SYS_EXIT_GROUP @Reasoning above). The wrapper's `Return`
    statement is unreachable under any defined kernel ABI — the syscall
    instruction transfers control to `sys_exit()` and never returns to the
    caller. Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 1
    (`SYS_exit`); `sys/kern/kern_exit.c` `sys_exit()`.

  syscall_brk -> SYS_BRK (17) via syscall_1: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `obreak(nsize)`, which is OpenBSD's name for the heap-break syscall.
    The kernel returns the resulting break address or -ENOMEM on failure.
    Argument shape is identical to Linux `brk(2)`. Source: OpenBSD
    `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 17 (`SYS_obreak`); `sys/kern/kern_resource.c`
    `sys_obreak()`.

  syscall_mmap -> SYS_MMAP (197) via syscall_6: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `mmap(addr, len, prot, flags, fd, offset)`. Six Integer arguments per
    the SysV AMD64 ABI (RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9). OpenBSD's mmap requires
    that anonymous mappings (MAP_ANONYMOUS|MAP_ANON) use `fd = -1` and
    `offset = 0`; the kernel rejects with -EINVAL otherwise. Note that
    OpenBSD's W^X enforcement requires that any executable mapping
    (PROT_EXEC) NOT also be writable (PROT_WRITE) without an explicit
    MAP_STACK or PROT_MPROTECT — the wrapper does not enforce this, the
    kernel does. Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 197 (`SYS_mmap`);
    `sys/uvm/uvm_mmap.c` `sys_mmap()`.

  syscall_munmap -> SYS_MUNMAP (73) via syscall_2: Direct forwarder to
    OpenBSD `munmap(addr, len)`. Returns 0 on success, -EINVAL if the
    region is not a multiple of the page size or if any byte in the range
    is unmapped (different from Linux which silently succeeds on
    partially-unmapped regions). Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry
    73 (`SYS_munmap`); `sys/uvm/uvm_mmap.c` `sys_munmap()`.

  syscall_fstat -> SYS_FSTAT (53) via syscall_2: Direct forwarder to OpenBSD
    `fstat(fd, sb)`. The `struct stat` layout on OpenBSD is documented in
    `sys/sys/stat.h` (152 bytes on AMD64 as of OpenBSD 7.4 — distinct from
    Linux's 144-byte layout); callers must pass a buffer of at least this
    size. Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 53 (`SYS_fstat`);
    `sys/kern/vfs_syscalls.c` `sys_fstat()`.

  syscall_lseek -> SYS_LSEEK (199) via syscall_3: Direct forwarder to
    OpenBSD `lseek(fd, offset, whence)`. The offset is passed as a
    single 64-bit register on AMD64 (entry 199 is the post-OpenBSD-5.5
    64-bit-clean entry; the legacy 166 = pad_lseek with split-halves ABI is
    obsolete and not used by this wrapper). Returns the new file offset or
    -ESPIPE if the fd is a pipe/socket/FIFO. Source: OpenBSD
    `sys/sys/syscall.h` entry 199 (`SYS_lseek`); `sys/kern/vfs_syscalls.c`
    `sys_lseek()`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper resolves its OpenBSD syscall number via the already-defined
SYS_<NAME>() getter (which the HIR -> MIR constant-fold pass collapses to
an immediate at every call site) and forwards to the appropriate
syscall_<N> generic dispatcher (`syscall_0` for zero-arg, `syscall_1` for
single-arg, ..., `syscall_6` for six-arg). The generic dispatchers (already
present in this file, lines emitting `Inline Assembly:` blocks) load the
syscall number into RAX and the arguments into the SysV AMD64 syscall
argument registers (RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9) before issuing the
`syscall` instruction. Unlike Darwin x86_64, OpenBSD does not OR a syscall-
class mask into RAX — the raw entry number is dispatched directly.

The wrapper layer adds no error translation: the kernel return value (a
non-negative result on success, a negative -errno on failure) is returned
verbatim to the Runa caller. Callers must use the `is_error()` helper (or
explicit `If result is less than 0:` comparison) to detect failure.

These wrappers are intentionally identical-in-shape to their counterparts
in every other platform's syscall.runa (Linux x86_64, Linux ARM64, FreeBSD
x86_64, etc.), differing only in the underlying SYS_<NAME>() value. The
shape uniformity is required by the dispatcher: `proc syscall_read from
OpenBSDX64` must have the same arity and argument convention as `proc
syscall_read from LinuxX86_64`, otherwise the dispatcher ladder cannot
forward calls without per-platform type munging.

syscall_brk does NOT need a sentinel guard on openbsd_x64 (unlike Darwin):
SYS_BRK=17 is a real syscall on OpenBSD, so the syscall instruction
executes normally. Callers requesting heap expansion will receive either
the new break address or -ENOMEM exactly like Linux brk(2).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
All ten wrappers are single-line forwarders with no branches, no allocations,
no locks, and no userland computation beyond the constant-fold of the
SYS_<NAME>() getter. The HIR -> MIR pass should reduce each wrapper body to
a single tail-call to syscall_<N> — equivalent in machine code to:

    syscall_read(fd, buf, nbyte):
        mov rax, 3              ; SYS_READ folded
        mov rdi, fd
        mov rsi, buf
        mov rdx, nbyte
        syscall
        ret

Performance is dominated by the kernel-side syscall path; the wrapper's
overhead is zero. The `syscall` instruction itself on AMD64 typically
costs ~50-100 cycles for the userland-to-kernel transition (varies by
CPU microarchitecture); none of these wrappers can be hot-path-optimized
beyond what the kernel ABI already permits.

OpenBSD's SROP (Sigreturn-Oriented Programming) mitigation and `pinsyscalls(2)`
restrict the *location* from which `syscall` may be issued (only from
addresses listed in the binary's PT_OPENBSD_SYSCALLS segment). The
generic syscall_<N> dispatchers in this file are linked into the
runtime's PT_OPENBSD_SYSCALLS segment via the build system; that is
external to the wrappers themselves but is a prerequisite for any wrapper
in this section to execute successfully.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Each wrapper inherits all security properties of its underlying OpenBSD
syscall. Specific concerns:

  syscall_read / syscall_write: kernel validates `fd` against the file
    descriptor table; invalid fd yields -EBADF. The buffer pointer and
    length are validated against the calling process's address space
    via `copyin`/`copyout` — out-of-bounds yields -EFAULT.

  syscall_open: kernel validates the path against the calling process's
    `unveil(2)` restrictions (if any) and `pledge(2)` promises (if any).
    Paths outside the unveiled set yield -ENOENT (deliberately
    indistinguishable from "file does not exist" to avoid information
    leak); attempts to open with O_WRONLY/O_RDWR/O_CREAT under a
    "rpath"-only pledge yield -EPERM. Production callers MUST be aware
    of the pledge/unveil contract of their enclosing process.

  syscall_close: kernel removes the fd from the descriptor table and
    drops the underlying object reference; double-close attempts yield
    -EBADF. The wrapper does NOT zero the caller's local `fd` variable
    after close — the caller must do that to prevent UAF-style errors
    if the descriptor is reused by a subsequent open.

  syscall_exit: irrevocable. The kernel destroys all process state. No
    finalizers, no deferred cleanup, no chance to recover.

  syscall_brk: kernel enforces the data-segment limit `RLIMIT_DATA` and
    the heap/mmap collision boundary; malicious values are rejected
    with -ENOMEM. The wrapper does not log or validate the requested
    break — that is the kernel's responsibility.

  syscall_mmap: kernel enforces W^X (no PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC mappings
    unless explicit `mimmutable(2)`/`pinsyscalls(2)` coordination), the
    ASLR base offset, and the `RLIMIT_AS` virtual-address-space limit.
    OpenBSD's `mmap` is more restrictive than Linux's: anonymous mappings
    MUST have fd=-1 and offset=0; the kernel returns -EINVAL otherwise.

  syscall_munmap: kernel verifies that every page in [addr, addr+len) is
    currently mapped; if any page is unmapped the entire call yields
    -EINVAL and no pages are unmapped (atomic semantics). This differs
    from Linux which silently succeeds on partially-unmapped ranges.

  syscall_fstat: kernel writes 152 bytes (OpenBSD AMD64 `struct stat`
    layout) to the caller-supplied buffer; insufficient buffer size
    yields -EFAULT during `copyout`.

  syscall_lseek: kernel validates the resulting offset against
    `off_t` range (signed 64-bit); offsets that overflow signed 64-bit
    yield -EOVERFLOW. On pipes/sockets/FIFOs the call yields -ESPIPE.

All wrappers must be invoked from a code path that satisfies the calling
process's `pledge(2)` promise set. The wrappers themselves do not assert
or relax pledge state — they execute under the inherited promises.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read from file descriptor (OpenBSD syscall 3)
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_READ()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write to file descriptor (OpenBSD syscall 4)
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_WRITE()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Open file (OpenBSD syscall 5); mode honored only when O_CREAT is set in flags
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_OPEN()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Close file descriptor (OpenBSD syscall 6)
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Terminate calling process (OpenBSD syscall 1); does not return
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_EXIT()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set program break (OpenBSD syscall 17, named obreak in syscall.h)
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_BRK()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map memory region (OpenBSD syscall 197); anonymous mappings require fd=-1, offset=0
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_MMAP()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unmap memory region (OpenBSD syscall 73); fails atomically on partially-unmapped ranges
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file status by descriptor (OpenBSD syscall 53); writes 152 bytes on AMD64
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reposition file offset (OpenBSD syscall 199, 64-bit-clean lseek)
    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_x64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on OpenBSD amd64.
    SYS_ioctl is 54 (OpenBSD sys/sys/syscall.h, frozen-historic
    4.4BSD numbering retained by OpenBSD to maintain ABI stability
    across releases). Three-arg shape (fd, request, argp). OpenBSD
    amd64 uses the standard System V AMD64 ABI (rdi, rsi, rdx) and
    the syscall instruction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling openbsd_x64_SYS_IOCTL() (returns
    54) and openbsd_x64_syscall_3(54, fd, cmd, arg). OpenBSD's
    syscall convention loads 54 into rax, fd into rdi, cmd into rsi,
    arg into rdx, then issues syscall; rax holds the result with the
    carry flag set on error (decoded inside syscall_3).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in the OpenBSD kernel — one fd-table lookup and a
    driver vtable jump. OpenBSD's ioctl path is among the most
    audited in BSD-land; the dispatch itself is sub-microsecond.
    Pledge(2)-restricted processes pay an additional check, but it
    is still a constant-time operation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The OpenBSD kernel validates fd against the per-process file
    descriptor table and dispatches cmd through fileops.fo_ioctl.
    arg, if a pointer, is dereferenced by the kernel with the
    structure size implied by cmd; callers must size the buffer to
    match. The pledge(2) mechanism enforces an ioctl-promise
    allowlist for processes that have pledged "tty" or "ioctl";
    callers should expect EPERM when invoked outside a pledged
    promise. Unveil(2) does not restrict ioctl directly but the fd
    itself may be restricted by an unveil(2) promise on the
    underlying file.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be openbsd_x64_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return openbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process
